7.4 Adding custom variables
While PatientProfiles provides a range of functions that can help you add characteristics of interest, you may also want to add other features. Obviously, the package canâ€™t cover all the possible custom characteristics you may wish to add. However, we will see two common groups of custom variables you may want to add:

variables derived from existing columns within the same table,
variables obtained from other tables and joined to our table of interest.

In the first case, where we want to add a new variable derived from existing variables within our table, weâ€™ll typically use mutate() (from the dplyr package). For example, perhaps we just want to add a new variable to our observation period table that contains the year of each individualâ€™s observation period start date. This is rather straightforward.

cdm$observation_period &lt;- cdm$observation_period |&gt;
  mutate(observation_period_start_year = get_year(observation_period_start_date))

cdm$observation_period |&gt;
  glimpse()

